.TH "rfd" "1" "2026-04-25"
.P
.SH NAME
.P
rfd - find files with GNU-style expressions and parallel traversal
.P
.SH SYNOPSIS
.P
\fBrfd\fR [\fB-H\fR|\fB-L\fR|\fB-P\fR] [\fB-O\fR_LEVEL_] [\fB-D\fR \fILIST\fR] [\fIPATH\fR.\&.\&.\&] [\fIEXPRESSION\fR]
.P
.SH DESCRIPTION
.P
\fBrfd\fR walks one or more start paths and evaluates an expression for each entry.\&
The default start path is the current directory.\& The default expression is
\fB-print\fR.\&
.P
The command line is intentionally close to GNU-style \fBfind\fR syntax, but this
manual describes the behavior implemented by \fBrfd\fR.\& The binary name is \fBrfd\fR;
the Rust package and project are named rushfind.\&
.P
By default, \fBrfd\fR uses physical traversal: command-line symbolic links and
symbolic links found during traversal are not followed.\& Use \fB-H\fR, \fB-L\fR, or \fB-P\fR
before start paths to select the global follow mode.\&
.P
.SH OPTIONS
.P
\fB-H\fR
.RS 4
Follow symbolic links listed as command-line start paths.\& Symbolic links
found during traversal are not followed.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-L\fR
.RS 4
Follow symbolic links while traversing.\& Directory link loops are detected
and reported instead of recursing forever.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-P\fR
.RS 4
Use physical traversal.\& This is the default.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-O\fR_LEVEL_
.RS 4
Accept a GNU-style optimizer level for command-line compatibility.\& The
current implementation records the level but does not change optimizer
behavior.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-D\fR \fILIST\fR
.RS 4
Enable lightweight debug diagnostics for comma-separated names.\& Valid
names are \fBexec\fR, \fBopt\fR, \fBrates\fR, \fBsearch\fR, \fBstat\fR, \fBtime\fR, \fBtree\fR, \fBall\fR,
and \fBhelp\fR.\& Use \fB-D help\fR to print the debug help text.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--help\fR
.RS 4
Print a compact quick reference and exit before traversal starts.\&
.P
.RE
\fB--version\fR, \fB-version\fR
.RS 4
Print build version metadata and exit before traversal starts.\&
.P
.RE
.SH EXPRESSIONS
.P
Expressions are made from tests, actions, operators, and traversal controls.\&
If no expression is supplied, \fBrfd\fR behaves as if \fB-print\fR was supplied.\&
.P
Adjacent primaries are joined by an implicit logical AND.\& Actions generally
return true when they succeed, allowing later expression terms to continue.\&
.P
.SH TESTS
.P
\fB-name\fR \fIPATTERN\fR, \fB-iname\fR \fIPATTERN\fR
.RS 4
Match the entry basename with a shell-style pattern.\& The \fBi\fR form is
case-insensitive.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-path\fR \fIPATTERN\fR, \fB-ipath\fR \fIPATTERN\fR
.RS 4
Match the full displayed path with a shell-style pattern.\& The \fBi\fR form is
case-insensitive.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-lname\fR \fIPATTERN\fR, \fB-ilname\fR \fIPATTERN\fR
.RS 4
Match the contents of a symbolic link.\& The \fBi\fR form is case-insensitive.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-regex\fR \fIPATTERN\fR, \fB-iregex\fR \fIPATTERN\fR
.RS 4
Match paths with the active regular-expression backend.\& The \fBi\fR form is
case-insensitive.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-regextype\fR \fITYPE\fR
.RS 4
Select the regular-expression syntax for following regex predicates.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-type\fR \fILIST\fR, \fB-xtype\fR \fILIST\fR
.RS 4
Match file type letters.\& Supported letters include \fBb\fR, \fBc\fR, \fBd\fR, \fBf\fR,
\fBl\fR, \fBp\fR, and \fBs\fR.\& Comma lists such as \fB-type f,d\fR are accepted.\& The
Solaris door type letter \fBD\fR is recognized for compatibility but reports
an unsupported diagnostic in this build.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-empty\fR
.RS 4
Match empty regular files or empty directories.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-size\fR \fIN\fR[\fBbckMGw\fR]
.RS 4
Match by file size using GNU-style numeric prefixes.\& A leading \fB+\fR means
greater than, a leading \fB-\fR means less than, and no prefix means exactly
the rounded unit count.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-mtime\fR \fIN\fR, \fB-atime\fR \fIN\fR, \fB-ctime\fR \fIN\fR
.RS 4
Match modification, access, or status-change time in days.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-mmin\fR \fIN\fR, \fB-amin\fR \fIN\fR, \fB-cmin\fR \fIN\fR
.RS 4
Match modification, access, or status-change time in minutes.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-newer\fR \fIFILE\fR, \fB-anewer\fR \fIFILE\fR, \fB-cnewer\fR \fIFILE\fR, \fB-newer\fR_XY_ \fIREFERENCE\fR
.RS 4
Compare timestamps with a reference file or supported literal timestamp.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-used\fR \fIN\fR
.RS 4
Match by days between last access and status change.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-uid\fR \fIN\fR, \fB-gid\fR \fIN\fR, \fB-user\fR \fINAME\fR, \fB-group\fR \fINAME\fR
.RS 4
Match numeric or named ownership where supported by the active platform.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-nouser\fR, \fB-nogroup\fR
.RS 4
Match entries whose owner or group cannot be resolved.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-perm\fR \fIMODE\fR
.RS 4
Match Unix-style permission modes where supported.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-readable\fR, \fB-writable\fR, \fB-executable\fR
.RS 4
Match using platform access checks.\& These are not simple permission-bit
tests.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-samefile\fR \fIFILE\fR, \fB-inum\fR \fIN\fR, \fB-links\fR \fIN\fR
.RS 4
Match identity and link-count metadata.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-fstype\fR \fITYPE\fR
.RS 4
Match entries by filesystem type using the active platform mount snapshot.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-true\fR, \fB-false\fR
.RS 4
Always return true or false.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-context\fR \fIPATTERN\fR
.RS 4
Recognized for SELinux compatibility, but SELinux context matching is not
supported by this build.\&
.P
.RE
.SH ACTIONS
.P
\fB-print\fR
.RS 4
Print the current path followed by a newline.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-print0\fR
.RS 4
Print the current path followed by a NUL byte.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-printf\fR \fIFORMAT\fR
.RS 4
Print formatted metadata.\& Supported directives include path directives
(\fB%p\fR, \fB%P\fR, \fB%H\fR, \fB%f\fR, \fB%h\fR), depth/type/size/mode/link directives,
owner/group directives, filesystem directives, and time directives.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-fprint\fR \fIFILE\fR, \fB-fprint0\fR \fIFILE\fR, \fB-fprintf\fR \fIFILE\fR \fIFORMAT\fR
.RS 4
Write print-style or printf-style output to a destination file.\& Destination
files are created or truncated during startup.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-ls\fR, \fB-fls\fR \fIFILE\fR
.RS 4
Render an ls-style record to stdout or a destination file.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-exec\fR \fICOMMAND\fR \fB;\fR, \fB-exec\fR \fICOMMAND\fR \fB+\fR
.RS 4
Run a command.\& The \fB+\fR form batches path arguments.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-execdir\fR \fICOMMAND\fR \fB;\fR, \fB-execdir\fR \fICOMMAND\fR \fB+\fR
.RS 4
Run a command from the matched entry'\&s parent directory.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-ok\fR \fICOMMAND\fR \fB;\fR, \fB-okdir\fR \fICOMMAND\fR \fB;\fR
.RS 4
Prompt before running a command.\& The batched \fB+\fR forms are not supported.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-delete\fR
.RS 4
Delete matched entries.\& This implies depth-mode traversal.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-quit\fR
.RS 4
Stop evaluation early.\& In relaxed parallel mode, already granted work may
still complete.\&
.P
.RE
.SH OPERATORS
.P
\fB( \fR\fIEXPRESSION\fR\fB )\fR
.RS 4
Group an expression.\&
.P
.RE
\fB!\&\fR \fIEXPRESSION\fR, \fB-not\fR \fIEXPRESSION\fR
.RS 4
Logical NOT.\&
.P
.RE
\fILEFT\fR \fB-a\fR \fIRIGHT\fR, \fILEFT\fR \fB-and\fR \fIRIGHT\fR
.RS 4
Logical AND.\& Adjacent primaries also imply AND.\&
.P
.RE
\fILEFT\fR \fB-o\fR \fIRIGHT\fR, \fILEFT\fR \fB-or\fR \fIRIGHT\fR
.RS 4
Logical OR.\&
.P
.RE
\fILEFT\fR \fB,\fR \fIRIGHT\fR
.RS 4
Evaluate expressions in sequence.\&
.P
.RE
.SH TRAVERSAL CONTROLS
.P
\fB-maxdepth\fR \fIN\fR
.RS 4
Descend at most \fIN\fR levels below each start path.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-mindepth\fR \fIN\fR
.RS 4
Do not apply the expression before depth \fIN\fR.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-depth\fR
.RS 4
Evaluate directories after their descendants.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-prune\fR
.RS 4
Return true and prevent traversal into the current directory in pre-order
mode.\& In depth mode, \fB-prune\fR remains true but does not prevent descendants.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-xdev\fR, \fB-mount\fR
.RS 4
Do not descend into directories on other filesystems.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-follow\fR
.RS 4
Accepted as a positional compatibility control and enables logical
symlink following for traversal.\&
.P
.RE
.SH COMPATIBILITY OPTIONS
.P
\fB-files0-from\fR \fIFILE\fR
.RS 4
Read NUL-terminated start paths from \fIFILE\fR.\& Use \fB-\fR to read from stdin.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-noleaf\fR
.RS 4
Accepted for compatibility and recorded; it does not change traversal.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-warn\fR, \fB-nowarn\fR
.RS 4
Accepted for compatibility and recorded as warning-mode preferences.\&
.P
.RE
\fB-ignore_readdir_race\fR, \fB-noignore_readdir_race\fR
.RS 4
Accepted for compatibility and recorded.\& The current implementation does
not yet alter runtime race handling for disappearing entries.\&
.P
.RE
.SH PRINTF FORMAT
.P
The \fB-printf\fR and \fB-fprintf\fR actions support GNU-style field formatting:
\fB%\fR[flags][width][\fB.\&precision\fR]\fIDIRECTIVE\fR.\& Common directives include \fB%p\fR
for the full displayed path, \fB%f\fR for the basename, \fB%h\fR for the dirname,
\fB%y\fR for file type, \fB%s\fR for size, \fB%m\fR and \fB%M\fR for modes, \fB%u\fR/\fB%g\fR for
owner and group names, \fB%U\fR/\fB%G\fR for numeric ownership, and \fB%a\fR/\fB%c\fR/\fB%t\fR
for timestamps.\&
.P
Escapes include \fB\\n\fR, \fB\\t\fR, \fB\\0\fR, \fB\\\\\fR, and \fB%%\fR.\& Unsupported directives
fail during planning with an explicit diagnostic.\&
.P
.SH PARALLEL EXECUTION
.P
Set \fBRUSHFIND_WORKERS=1\fR for ordered single-worker traversal.\& Values greater
than one enable relaxed-order parallel traversal.\&
.P
Parallel mode may emit output and side effects in an order different from GNU
style sibling traversal.\& It preserves documented structural constraints such
as prune boundaries and depth-mode descendant-before-parent completion.\&
.P
Lightweight debug diagnostics from \fB-D\fR describe \fBrfd\fR internals; they are not
a full GNU findutils trace stream.\&
.P
.SH EXIT STATUS
.P
\fB0\fR
.RS 4
The command completed successfully.\&
.P
.RE
\fB1\fR
.RS 4
A parse, planning, traversal, action, or output error occurred.\&
.P
.RE
.SH EXAMPLES
.P
Find Rust files below \fBsrc\fR:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
rfd src -name \&'*\&.rs\&' -print
.fi
.RE
.P
Print NUL-terminated large regular-file paths:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
rfd \&. -type f -size +1M -print0
.fi
.RE
.P
Skip target directories while printing regular files:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
rfd \&. -name target -prune -o -type f -print
.fi
.RE
.P
Read start paths from a NUL-delimited file:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
rfd -files0-from roots\&.list -type f -print
.fi
.RE
.P
Run a command for each matching file:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
rfd \&. -type f -exec sh -c \&'printf "%s\\n" "$1"\&' sh {} ;
.fi
.RE
.P
Print selected metadata:
.P
.nf
.RS 4
rfd \&. -type f -printf \&'%p %s\\n\&'
.fi
.RE
.P
.SH CAVEATS
.P
Some recognized compatibility features are intentionally unsupported in this
build and fail before traversal starts.\& These include SELinux \fB-context\fR
matching and Solaris door matching through \fB-type D\fR or \fB-xtype D\fR.\&
.P
On non-Linux and Windows platforms, some metadata predicates use platform
backends and may differ where the host exposes different filesystem or account
semantics.\&
.P
.SH SEE ALSO
.P
